entry.title: Ensure restarted animations don't clobber start time
entry.content:
The bug here occurs because of a race. Blink Animations can be

invalidated for all sorts of reasons and they require cancelling the

current cc::Animation and starting a new one. When this happens, the new

cc::Animation will use the start time that was received for the original

Animation.



The race condition occurs when the Blink Animation is invalidated before

a start time is received. In that case, the Animation starts playing on

the impl thread but the new Animation is created without a start time,

leading to the Animation starting from the beginning, causing a stutter

effect. Additionally, animation events generated on the impl thread when

Blink invalidates an animation are dropped since the main thread

counterpart is gone by the time of the events arrive.



This CL fixes the issue by making Blink recreate the compositor

animation with the same id and setting a bit on it to make it reuse

the start time from the compositor animation when it is pushed. The

animation also reuses the compositor group id on a restarted animation

so that animation events are routed back to the blink::Animation

correctly.



Bug: 1445090

entry.title: Fix criteria for inheritance stopping incremental style calculation.
entry.content:
Our current check for whether change in a parent element should stop

incremental style updates (MISU) is broken; it did not properly take

into account that the parent may have changes that we should include.



We also noticed that this code is called from a number of unexpected

paths (e.g. the layout code sometimes needs to resolve style for

inherited ::first-line, without the element actually being dirty).



We flip the “can use incremental style” default from true to false

to be safe in both of these cases.

entry.title: [SAA] Inherit the context's storage-access bit for WebSockets
entry.content:
This plumbs the has_storage_access bool from the WebSocket's

ExecutionContext to the network service machinery, so that a

Document's or Worker's Storage Access API opt-in is respected for

WebSocket connections. (Note that this bit is untrusted; a compromised

renderer cannot gain unauthorized access to unpartitioned cookies by

lying with this bit.)



This behavior is currently unspecified by the Storage Access API spec,

but we will engage there to specify it. In the meantime, web

developers expect the API to work this way (see

https://crbug.com/947413#c20).



I plan to add WPTs for this in a followup, but I'd like to land this

before branch cut if possible.

entry.title: [mask] Avoid const_cast in ParseBackgroundOrMask (AddBackgroundValue)
entry.content:
ParseBackgroundOrMask avoids an enclosing CSSValueList when that

list contains a single item, and instead just represents the single

value directly. This is fine, but to satisfy various APIs that need

to cooperate, we have a const_cast in AddBackgroundValue, which isn't

robust in an evolving code base. Illegally modifying the result of

Longhand::InitialValue() would be particularly bad, since InitialValue

functions often use DEFINE_STATIC_LOCAL to avoid creating identical

values over and over.



This CL refactors to *avoid* the const_cast, by collecting the items

bound for the list before actually creating the CSSValueList.

This is also in line with the greater ambition of making CSSValueList

entry.title: Improve NGLayoutInputNode debug dumping.
entry.content:
Support dumping the entire document and mark the target node with '*'.

Also support dumping to a string, in addition to LOG(INFO).



When dumping the NGLayoutInputNode tree, also descend into block nodes

inside inline nodes. This includes floats, atomic inlines,

block-in-inline and out-of-flow positioned elements.



Clean up dumping of InlineNode. Instead of:

"InlineItem. Type: '%s'. LayoutObject: '%s'"

simply do:

"InlineItem %s. %s"



... except when it's text, in which case we'll dump the actual text

instead of the LayoutObject debug name.



Omit quotes around the debug name in NGBlockNode::ToString() as well. It

was hard to read when the element had attributes.



When visiting an InlineNode, DCHECK that it doesn't have siblings.

InlineNode::NextSibling() always returns nullptr. It should be removed.

I'll do that in a separate CL.



Add a few unit tests.

entry.title: Fix the crash caused by CHECK for the url comparison
entry.content:
This is the fix CL for the crash bug in crbug.com/1492640. The crash is

caused by CHECK_EQ(), which checks if the deduped request URL is same as

the one from the network request triggered for the race request.



We identified the crash happens when the request is intercepted by some

extensions e.g. ad blockers. They are able to change the deduped URL

from `https://~` to `chrome-extension://`. We compare the changed URL

with the original start url, and that hits CHECK error.



This URLLoaderFactory just fuses two mojo endpoints into one. That can

be called multiple times inside the blink's ThrottlingURLLoader [1].

Also this URLLoaderFactory is used only when the corresponding request

from the fetch handler is detected. As far as the detection is baesd on

the base::UnguessableToken match, we can trust that the upcoming request

is same as the network request dispatched for the race. We don't have to

have additional the URL comparison, which caused this crash.



This URLLoaderFactory was designed to work for the dedupe by fusing

pipes, but when the request is respond with the internal redirect and

the new url starts with the exntesion prorocol, the force restart of

throttling_url_loader is called and CreateLoaderAndStart() in

ServiceWorkerForwardedRaceNetworkRequestURLLoaderFactory can be called

multiple times [2]. This CL addressed that case by changing the

URLLoaderFactory initiates the new request when CreateLoaderAndStart()

is called but the message pipes are already fused.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/common/loader/throttling_url_loader.cc;l=607

[2] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/renderer/platform/loader/fetch/url_loader/resource_request_sender.cc;l=644



Bug: 1492640

entry.title: Remove unused policy opcode definitions
entry.content:
The policy opcode engine lives deep in the sandbox and is used to

match function parameters on the stack before allowing or denying

calls proxied by the sandbox broker.



The engine 'supports' a number of operations which were never

implemented or are no longer used (policy_engine_opcodes.h):



Ops:



OP_NUMBER_MATCH_RANGE



Statuses:



GIVE_READONLY,

GIVE_ALLACCESS,

GIVE_CACHED,

GIVE_FIRST,

TERMINATE_PROCESS,



Additionally string matching allowed for case-sensitive and

case-insensitive matching but in practice only case-insensitive

matching was ever used. This option-type and related parameters

are removed. Some tests are changed to use case-insensitive matching

as those tests concern construction of opcode sequences rather than

the implementation of the match opcodes themselves.
